Viva Questions
--------------------------------------------------

1. What is a Soft Link?
2. What is a Hard Link?
3. Which command creates a Soft Link?
4. Which command creates a Hard Link?
5. What is an inode?
6. Which command displays inode numbers?
7. Which link has the same inode as the original file?
8. Which link has a different inode number?
9. What happens when the original file of a Soft Link is deleted?
10. What happens when the original file of a Hard Link is deleted?
11. Can Soft Links be created across different file systems?
12. Can Hard Links be created across different file systems?
13. Can Soft Links be created for directories?
14. Can Hard Links be created for directories?
15. What is a hanging link?
16. What is the purpose of the stat command?
17. What is the purpose of the unlink command?
18. What information is stored in an inode?
19. How do you check inode numbers using ls?
20. How do you check inode details using stat?

Conclusion
==========

1. Soft Link is a shortcut that points to the original file or directory.
2. Hard Link is another name for the same file.
3. Soft Link has a different inode number.
4. Hard Link has the same inode number.
5. Soft Link can link files and directories.
6. Hard Link can link only files.
7. Soft Link becomes broken when the original file is deleted.
8. Hard Link continues to work even after the original file is deleted.
9. Inode stores metadata such as owner, permissions, size, timestamps and disk location.
